  From (7) we find that  and there is no problem as long as we consider the tachyonic
model of inflation in phenomenological context. However, it would be problematic if we trace the origin of
field  in string theory as there is no free parameter there to tune. Indeed,  and 
 can be expressed through string length scale and string coupling   as ,   
  where  and  are dimensionless constants and  is brane tension and
 is the tachyon mass. Tuning  to  leads to one of the two unacceptable situations: light mass
of the tachyon or large value of string coupling . This problem is quite independent of the form of tachyonic potential, see the paper of  Fairbairn and Tytgat Ref. The situation can be remedied by invoking the large number of
D-branes separated by distance much larger than (We thank S. Panda for this clarification) . The number of such branes in our case turns out to be of the order of
. The other alternative could be brane assisted inflation. Indeed, the prospects of inflation in Brane World scenario
improve due to the presence of an additional quadratic density term in the
Friedmann equation. Enough inflation
can be generated in this case without tuning , see the paper by Bento et al and Ref.
The non-brane world  alternatives to tackle this problem are discussed by Yun-Song Piao and collaborators. Regarding the late time behaviour, the  phase space analysis  of tachyon field with exponential potential was carried out in Ref
. It was shown that dust like solution is a late time attractor of the tachyonic system.
Therefore the tachyon field , in principal, could  become a candidate for  dark matter.Inspite of the very attractive features of the rolling tachyon condensate, the tachyonic inflation
faces difficulties associated with reheating. A homogeneous tachyon field evolves towards its
ground state without oscillating about it and , therefore, the  conventional reheating
mechanism in tachyonic model does not work. Quantum mechanical particle
production during inflation  provides an alternative mechanism by means of
which the universe could reheat. Unfortunately, this mechanism also does not seem to
work: the  small energy density of
radiation  created in this process red-shifts faster than the energy density of the tachyon field and therefore radiation
domination in the tachyonic model of inflation never commences. However, the tachyon field
could play the  role of  dark matter if the problem associated with caustics could be overcome. 
